@node "Examples" "Examples"
 @{"M82" link "M82" 0}
 @{"MilkyWay" link "MilkyWay" 0}
 @{"Nessie" link "Nessie" 0}
 @{"NGC6946" link "NGC6946" 0}
 @{"NGC6992" link "NGC6992" 0}
 @{"WhirlPool" link "WhirlPool" 0}
@endnode

@node "M82" "M82"
Dist. 10.5E6 LY. The most popular example of an exploding galaxy. And the
good example of @{"manual drawing" link "Mouse draw" 0}, combining different @{"Denses" link "Dense" 0}, and turning on
(for left half) and off (for right half) @{"Redense" link "Redense" 0} option.
@endnode

@node "MilkyWay" "MilkyWay"
Our galaxy. Simply the most beautifull of all.
@endnode

@node "Nessie" "Nessie"
Example of @{"manual drawing" link "Mouse draw" 0}. I have to admit that this isn't a galaxy, but who
cares:)
@endnode

@node "NGC6946" "NGC6946"
This is a good example for use of @{"Redense" link "Redense" 0} option.
@endnode

@node "NGC6992" "NGC6992"
Dist: 2500 LY. In fact, this isn't a galaxy, but a planetary nebula. Note
that, when you are drawing a galaxy, using only one @{"arm" link "1234C" 0}, it's slightly
faster to turn off the @{"Same" link "Same" 0} option.
@endnode

@node "WhirlPool" "WhirlPool"
M51, dist. 37E6 LY, this galaxy is an example on how to combine manual and
automaticall drawing.
@endnode

@node "Pirates!" "Pirates!"

                                   Pirates

I have to admit that all software used in developing of this program is
pirated, or shareware. Yes, I know it's ugly, but think about: in Yugoslavia
there is no any distributer for commercial software, and even if there is, I
couldn't afford it. So, I think that it's better to use pirated software,
than none; after all, it's only harder for me to work without instructions,
and besides, you would never be watching this program.
@endnode

